result.execSummary:
The defendant Colin D. Gile was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Colin D. Gile appeared, James T. Sempf appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called @ 9:30 a.m. Appearances made. Matter before the Court for initial appearance. Discussion with the defendant as to decision regarding attorney. Defendant would like to waive his attorney so he can see speak to the State. Court provides waiver of attorney paperwork to the defendant to fill out and will recall case. In recess @ 9:41 a.m.
10:02 a.m. - Case recalled. Court goes over waiver form with the defendant, who responds to Court's questions. Court finds waiver to be knowing, voluntary, and intelligent. Court enters not guilty plea on defendant's behalf and informs him to go downstairs to the DA's office to set up appointment with Atty. Berg. Court sets for status hearing about 30 days out. Court in recess.  Status conference scheduled for February 14, 2022 at 08:30 am.
